
[1]agitate

   AG'ITATE, v.t. [L. agito, from ago. See Act.]

   1. To stir violently; to move back and forth with a quick motion; to
   shake or move briskly; as, to agitate water in a vessel.

   2. To move or force into violent irregular action; as, the wind
   agitates the sea.

   3. To disturb, or excite into tumult; as, to agitate the mind or
   passions.

   4. To discuss; to debate; to controvert; as, to agitate a question.

   5. To consider on all sides; to revolve in the mind, or view in all its
   aspects; to contrive by mental deliberation; as, politicians agitate
   desperate designs.

   6. To move or actuate. [Not used.]
